ge triggers and are simultaneously\nvery long, faint, and `soft' hard-X-ray transients. The BAT data alone can\ndiscriminate very well the SFXTs from other fast transients such as anomalous\nX-ray pulsars and soft gamma repeaters. However, to distinguish SFXTs from, for\ninstance, accreting millisecond X-ray pulsars and jetted tidal disruption\nevents, the XRT data collected around the time of the BAT triggers are\ndecisive. The XRT observations of 35/52 SFXT BAT triggers show that in the soft\nX-ray energy band, SFXTs display a decay in flux from the peak of the outburst\nof at least 3 orders of magnitude within a day and rarely undergo large\nre-brightening episodes, favouring in most cases a rapid decay down to the\nquiescent level within 3-5 days (at most). [Abridged]\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Fri, 9 Dec 2022 19:01:33 GMT"}],"update_date":"2023-02-22"}
